FR941005-2-00110 FR941005-2-00078 Notice of Determinations Regarding Eligibility to Apply for Worker Adjustment Assistance and NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance In accordance with Section 223 of the Trade Act of 1974, as amended, the Department of Labor herein presents summaries of determinations regarding eligibility to apply for trade adjustment assistance for workers (TA&hyph;W) issued during the period of September, 1994. In order for an affirmative determination to be made and a certification of eligibility to apply for worker adjustment assistance to be issued, each of the group eligibility requirements of Section 222 of the Act must be met. (1) That a significant number or proportion of the workers in the workers' firm, or an appropriate subdivision thereof, have become totally or partially separated, (2) That sales or production, or both, of the firm or subdivision have decreased absolutely, and (3) That increases of imports of articles like or directly competitive with articles produced by the firm or appropriate subdivision have contributed importantly to the separations, or threat thereof, and to the absolute decline in sales or production. Negative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance In each of the following cases the investigation revealed that criterion (3) has not been met. A survey of customers indicated that increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,173; International Paper Container Div., Presque Isle, ME TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,124; F.C.I., Freeman SD TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,939; Commercial Flight Systems Div. of Honeywell, Phoenix, AZ TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,038; NEC America, Inc., Hillsboro, OR TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,969; Kollmorgen Corp., Inland Motor Div., Radford, VA TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,772; Wilmington Steel & Construction, Inc., New Castle, PA TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,136; Roeder Hydraulic, Inc., DBA Universal Service & Supply Co., Odessa, TX TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,074; Cominco Metals, Magmont Operations, Bixby, MO In the following cases, the investigation revealed that the criteria for eligibility have not been met for the reasons specified. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,287; Code-A-Phone Corp., Clackamas, OR The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,042; Air Products & Chemicals, Inc., Wilkes Barre, PA Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,095; Brad Hagood Farms, Lubbock, TX Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,873; Allied Signal Aerospace Co., Government Electronic Systems, Teterboro, NJ U.S. imports of aircraft parts decreased absolutely in the latest twelve month period April 1993_March 1994 compared with the same period one year earlier. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,087; Walport USA, Elizabeth, NJ The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974.
